he Great Physician" from Prescriptions Worth a Thousand in Gold -- t54. Using the Golden Needle: Nagaljuna Bodhisattva's Ophthalmological Treatise and Other Sources in the Essentials of Medical Treatment -- t55. Buddhism in Choson Dynasty Medical Compilations -- t56. Determining Karmic Illness: Kajiwara Shozen's Treatment of Rai/Leprosy in Book of the Simple Physician -- t57. Selections from Miraculous Drugs of the South, by the Vietnamese Buddhist Monk-Physician TueTinh -- t58. The Dong Nhan Pagoda and the Publication of Mister Lazy's Medical Encyclopedia -- t59. An Abhidhamma Perspective: Causes of Illness in a Burmese Buddhist Medical System -- t60.Jewels in Medicines: On the Processing and Efficacy of Precious Pills According to the Four Treatises -- t61. The Final Doubt and the Entrustment of Tibetan Medical Knowledge -- t62. Did the Buddha Really Author the Classic Tibetan Medical Text? A Critical Examination from The Lamp to Dispel Darkness -- tAppendix: Geographical Table of Contents -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its earliest days, Buddhism has been closely intertwined with medicine. Buddhism and Medicine is a singular collection showcasing the generative relationship and mutual influence between these fields across premodern Asia. The anthology combines dozens of English-language translations of premodern Buddhist texts with contextualizing introductions by leading international scholars in Buddhist studies, the history of medicine, and a range of other fields.These sources explore in detail medical topics ranging from the development of fetal anatomy in the womb to nursing, hospice, dietary regimen, magical powers, visualization, and other healing knowledge. Works translated here include meditation guides, popular narratives, ritual manuals, spells texts, monastic disciplinary codes, recipe inscriptions, philosophical treatises, poetry, works by physicians, and other genres. All together, these selections and their introductions provide a comprehensive overview of Buddhist healing throughout Asia. They also demonstrate the central place of healing in Buddhist practice and in the daily life of the premodern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHealingxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aMedicinexReligious aspectsxBuddhismvSources. 0aSufferingxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aAhn, Juhn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreeva, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAniilayo,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBingenheimer, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapitanio, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoompolpaisal, Phibul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopp, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrott, Edward R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuckworth, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiordalis, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerke, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiddings, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoble, Andrew Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranoff, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Eric M., econtributor.4ctb4https://i